{"parse":{"title":"hello","pageid":4803,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|helló}}\n\n==English==\n{{phrasebook|en|Greetings}}\n{{was wotd|2007|November|19}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|hallo||UK|_|old style}}\n* {{alt|en|hilloa||obsolete}}\n* {{alt|en|hullo||UK}}\n\n===Etymology===\n''Hello'' (first attested in 1826), from {{m|en|holla}}, {{m|en|hollo}} (attested 1588). This variant of {{m|en|hallo}} is often credited to [[w:Thomas Edison|Thomas Edison]] as a coinage for telephone use, but its appearance in print predates the invention of the telephone by several decades.\n\nUltimately from a variant of Old English {{m|ang|ēalā}}, such as {{m|ang|hēlā}}, which was used colloquially at the time similarly to how ''hey'' and (in some dialects) ''hi'' are used nowadays. Thus, equivalent to a compound of {{m|en|hey}} and {{m|en|lo}}. Used when drawing attention to yourself.\n\nPossibly influenced by {{ncog|osx|halo|halo!}}, imperative of {{m|osx|halōn|t=to call, fetch}}, used in hailing a ferryman, akin to {{ncog|goh|hala}}, {{m|goh|hola|hola!}}, imperative forms of {{m|goh|halōn}}, {{m|goh|holōn|t=to fetch}}. More at {{l|en|hallo}}.\n\nOED and Merriam-Webster also suggested that it is a variant of {{m|en|holla}}, a variant of {{m|en|holloo}}. Further beyond, the origin remains uncertain. OED and Merriam-Webster suggested that it has a connection between {{m|en|hallow|t= to shout, to cry out loud}}, which came from Old French {{m|fro|holloer}}, which, according to ''Altfranzösisches Wörterbuch'', is from {{cog|osx|halōn}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/hɛˈloʊ/|/həˈloʊ/|/ˈhɛloʊ/|a=GA}}, {{enPR|hĕ-lō'|hə-lō'}}\n* {{a|en|UK}}\n** {{IPA|en|/həˈləʊ/|/hɛˈləʊ/|a=RP}}\n** {{IPA|en|/hæˈlaʊ/|a=Northumbrian}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-hello.ogg|a=UK}}\n* {{IPA|en|/həˈləʉ/|a=AU}}\n** {{audio|en|En-au-hello.ogg|a=AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/hɛˈloː/|/həˈloː/|/ˈhɛloː/|/ˈhɛlo/|a=CA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/həˈlo(w)/|a=Indic}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛləʊ|s=2}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Sense\n! UK\n! US\n|-\n|{{sense|greeting}}\n|{{audio|en|en-uk-hello-1.ogg|a=UK}}\n|{{audio|en|en-us-hello.ogg|a=US}}\n|-\n|{{sense|telephone greeting}}\n|{{audio|en|en-uk-hello-2.ogg|a=UK}}\n|{{audio|en|en-us-hello-2.ogg|a=US}}\n|-\n|{{sense|call for response}}\n|{{audio|en|en-uk-hello-3.ogg|a=UK}}\n|{{audio|en|en-us-hello-3.ogg|a=US}}\n|-\n|{{sense|sarcastic implication}}\n|{{audio|en|en-uk-hello-4.ogg|a=UK}}\n|{{audio|en|en-us-hello-4.ogg|a=US}}\n|-\n|{{sense|expressing puzzlement}}\n|{{audio|en|en-uk-hello-5.ogg|a=UK}}\n|\n|}\n* {{rhymes|en|əʊ|s=2}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{en-intj}}\n\n# {{ng|A [[greeting]] ([[salutation]]) said when [[meet]]ing someone or [[acknowledge|acknowledging]] someone’s [[arrival]] or [[presence]].}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Hello''', everyone.}}\n# {{ng|A greeting used when [[answer]]ing the [[telephone]].}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Hello'''? How may I help you?}}\n#* '''2016''', [https://web.archive.org/web/20170918070146/https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/lets-learn-english-lesson-3-i-am-here/3126527.html VOA Learning English] (public domain)\n#*: '''Hello'''. This is Marsha. ― Yes, Marsha.\n# {{ng|A call for [[response]] if it is not clear if anyone is present or listening, or if a telephone conversation may have been [[disconnect]]ed.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Hello'''? Is anyone there?}}\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=7|passage=I made a speaking trumpet of my hands and commenced to whoop “Ahoy!” and “'''Hello!'''” at the top of my lungs. {{...}} The Colonel woke up, and, after asking what in brimstone was the matter, opened his mouth and roared “Hi!” and “'''Hello!'''” like the bull of Bashan.}}\n# {{lb|en|colloquial}} {{ng|Used [[sarcastic]]ally to imply that the person addressed has done something the speaker considers to be [[foolish]], or missed something that should have been [[obvious]].}}\n#: {{ux|en|You just tried to start your car with your cell phone. '''Hello'''?}}\n#* {{quote-video game|en|year=2004|title=w:Paper Mario: The Thousand-Year Door|developer=Intelligent Systems|publisher=Nintendo|system=GameCube|level=Rogueport|translator=Nintendo of America|text=Uh, '''hello'''? We're using a CANNON to get to the moon? Isn't that, like, dangerous?}}\n# {{lb|en|chiefly|UK}} {{ng|An expression of [[puzzlement]] or [[discovery]].}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Hello'''! What’s going on here?}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* The greeting {{m|en|hello}} is among the most universal and neutral in use. It may be heard in nearly all social situations and nearly all walks of life and is unlikely to offend.\n\n*In the derived  senses, the word-final stress may be emphasized to focus attention, but word-initial stress is also heard in certain contexts, such as some uses of {{m|en|hello there}}, and even in isolation.\n\n====Quotations====\n* {{see citations|en}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|greeting}} {{see thesaurus|en|hello}}\n** {{qualifier|Australia, informal}} [[g'day]], [[hey]], [[hi]]\n** {{qualifier|UK, informal}} [[hallo]], [[hi]], [[hiya]], [[ey up]], [[you alright]], [[alright]]\n** {{qualifier|US, informal}} [[hallo]], [[hey]], [[hi]], [[howdy]]\n** {{qualifier|Ireland, informal}} [[how's it going]], [[hey]], [[hi]]\n** {{qualifier|South Africa, informal}} [[howzit]]\n** {{qualifier|slang}} [[wassup]], [[what's up]], [[yo]], [[sup]], [[what's good]]\n* {{sense|expression of puzzlement}} {{see thesaurus|en|wow}}\n\n====Antonyms====\n* {{antsense|greeting}} {{l|en|bye}}, {{l|en|goodbye}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|golden hello\n|hello again\n|hello girl\n|helloji\n|hello nurse\n|hello there|say hello\n|Hello World\n|hello yourself, and see how you like it\n|yello\n}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|hy|հէլօ|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|am|ሀሎ|tr=halo|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|zh|哈嘍|哈囉|哈佬|tr3=hālǎo|哈咯|ciallo|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ja|ハロー|tr=harō|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ms|helo|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|gd|halò|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|cy|helo|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|acm|هلو|bor=1}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|greeting}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Abaza: {{tt|abq|сальам}}\n* Abkhaz: {{tt|ab|бзиа збаша}}, {{tt|ab|мыш бзи}}, {{qualifier|to a man}} {{tt|ab|бзиара убааит}}, {{qualifier|to a woman}} {{tt|ab|бзиара ббааит}}, {{qualifier|to more than one person}} {{tt|ab|бзиара жәбааит|p}}\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+|af|hallo}}, {{t|af|goeiedag}}\n* Ahom: {{tt|aho|𑜈𑜩𑜨 𑜀𑜪𑜨}}\n* Ainu: {{tt|ain|イランカラㇷ゚テ|tr=irankarapte}}\n* Akan: {{t|ak|maakye}} {{qualifier|morning}}, {{t|ak|maaha}} {{qualifier|afternoon}}, {{t|ak|maadwo}} {{qualifier|evening}}\n* Albanian: {{tt+|sq|përshëndetje}}, {{tt+|sq|tungjatjeta}}, {{tt|sq|tung}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt|sq|ç'kemi|m|f}}\n*: Arbëresh Albanian: {{t+|aae|falem}}\n* Aleut: {{tt|ale|aang}}, {{tt|ale|draas}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{t|alt|эзен}}, {{t|alt|селем}}\n* Alutiiq: {{t|ems|cama’i}}\n* Ambonese Malay: {{tt|abs|wai}}\n* American Sign Language: {{tt|ase|B@Sfhead-PalmForward B@FromSfhead-PalmForward}}\n* Amharic: {{tt|am|ሰላም}}\n* Apache:\n*: Jicarilla: {{tt|apj|dá nzhǫ́}}\n*: Western Apache: {{tt|apw|dagotʼee}}, {{tt|apw|daʼanzho}}, {{tt|apw|yaʼateh}}\n* Arabic: {{tt+|ar|السَّلَامُ عَلَيْكُمْ}}, {{tt+|ar|سَلَام}}, {{tt+|ar|مَرْحَبًا}}, {{tt+|ar|أَهْلًا}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|اهلاً|tr=ahlan}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t|acw|مَرحَبا|tr=marḥaba}}, {{t|acw|هلا|tr=hala}}, {{t|acw|السلام عليكم|tr=as-salāmu ʕalēkum}}, {{t|acw|أهلًا|tr=ʔahlan}}\n*: Iraqi Arabic: {{tt|acm|هلو|tr=helaww}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{t|aii|ܫܠܵܡܵܐ}}, {{t|aii|ܫܠܵܡܵܐ ܥܲܠܘܼܟ݂}} {{q|formal; to a male}}, {{t|aii|ܫܠܵܡܵܐ ܥܲܠܵܟ݂ܝ}} {{q|formal; to a female}}, {{t|aii|ܫܠܵܡܵܐ ܥܲܠܵܘܟ݂ܘܿܢ}} {{q|formal; to a group}}\n* Archi: {{tt|aqc|салам алейкум}}, {{tt|aqc|варчӏами}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|բարև}} {{qualifier|addressed to a single familiar person}}, {{tt|hy|բարև ձեզ}} {{qualifier|addressed to several people}}, {{tt|hy|բարև Ձեզ}} {{qualifier|formal, addressed to a single unfamiliar person}}, {{tt+|hy|ողջույն}}\n* Assamese: {{tt|as|নমস্কাৰ}} {{q|very formal}}, {{tt|as|আচ্চেলামো আলাইকোম}} {{q|formal|used among Muslims}}, {{tt|as|হেল’}}\n* Asturian: {{tt+|ast|hola}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{tt+|az|salam}}, {{tt|az|səlam}} {{q|South Azerbaijani}}, {{tt|az|hər vaxtınız xeyir olsun}}, {{tt|az|hər vaxtınız xeyir}}, {{t|az|günaydın}}, {{t|az|xoş gördük}}, {{t|az|əssəlamü əleyküm}}\n* Bambara: {{t|bm|i ni ce}}\n* Bashkir: {{tt|ba|сәләм}}\n* Basque: {{tt+|eu|kaixo}}\n* Bats: {{t-needed|bbl}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|віта́ю}}, {{tt|be|здаро́ў}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}, {{tt|be|прыве́т}}, {{tt|be|до́бры дзень}} {{qualifier|good day}}\n* Bengali: {{tt+|bn|আসসালামু আলাইকুম}}, {{tt+|bn|সালাম}}, {{tt+|bn|নমস্কার}}, {{tt+|bn|হ্যালো}}\n* Bhojpuri: {{t|bho|प्रणाम}}\n* Bouyei: {{tt|pcc|mengz ndil}}\n* Breton: {{t-needed|br}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|здра́сти}} {{qualifier|familiar}}, {{tt+|bg|здраве́й|s}} {{qualifier|familiar}}, {{tt+|bg|здраве́йте|p}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n* Burmese: {{tt+|my|မင်္ဂလာပါ}} <!-- lit. \"it's a blessing!, ပါ (ba) is a particle\" -->, {{tt+|my|ဟဲလို}}\n* Carpathian Rusyn: {{tt|rue|наздар}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|hola}}\n* Cayuga: {{tt|cay|sgę́꞉nǫʼ}}\n* Central Atlas Tamazight: {{tt|tzm|ⴰⵣⵓⵍ}}\n* Chamorro: {{tt|ch|håfa adai}}\n* Chechen: {{tt|ce|маршалла ду хьоьга}} {{qualifier|to one person}}, {{tt|ce|маршалла ду шуьга}} {{qualifier|to a group of people}}, {{tt|ce|ассаламу ӏалайкум}}\n* Cherokee: {{tt+|chr|ᎣᏏᏲ}}\n* Chichewa: {{tt|ny|moni}}\n* Chickasaw: {{tt|cic|chokma}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{tt|yue|你好|tr=nei5 hou2}}, {{tt|yue|哈佬|tr=haa1 lou2}}\n*: Dungan: {{tt|dng|ни хо}}, {{tt|dng|сэляму}}, {{tt|dng|хома}}\n*: Eastern Min: {{tt|cdo|汝好|tr=nṳ̄ hō̤}}\n*: Hakka: {{tt|hak|你好|tr=ngì-hó}}\n*: Hokkien: {{tt|nan-hbl|汝好|tr=lí hó}}\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|你好|tr=nǐ hǎo}}, {{tt+|cmn|您好|tr=nín hǎo}} {{qualifier|polite}}, {{tt|cmn|你們好|tr=nǐmen hǎo}} {{qualifier|to a group of people}}, {{tt+|cmn|好|tr=hǎo}} {{qualifier|following an address form or name}}, {{tt+|cmn|嗨|tr=hāi}}, {{tt+|cmn|哈囉|tr=hāluó}}, {{t|cmn|ciallo}} {{qualifier|slang}}\n*: Wu: {{tt|wuu|儂好}}\n*: Xiang: {{t-needed|hsn}}\n* Choctaw: {{tt|cho|halito}}\n* Chukchi: {{tt|ckt|еттык|tr=ettyk}} {{qualifier|formal}}, {{tt|ckt|ети|tr=eti}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt|ckt|етти|tr=etti}} {{qualifier|informal}}\n* Circassian:\n*: East Circassian: {{tt|kbd|уузыншэм}}\n*: West Circassian: {{t-needed|ady}}\n* Coptic: {{tt|cop|ⲛⲟϥⲣⲓ}}\n* Cornish: {{tt|kw|dydh da}}\n* Corsican: {{tt|co|bonghjornu}}\n* Cree:\n*: Plains Cree: {{tt|crk|tânisi}}\n* Crimean Tatar:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|crh|Мераба}}\n*: Latin: {{tt|crh|Meraba}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|ahoj}}, {{tt+|cs|nazdar}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt+|cs|čau}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt+|cs|dobrý den}} {{q|formal}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|hej}}, {{tt+|da|dav}}, {{tt|da|god dag}} {{qualifier|formal}}, {{tt+|da|hallo}}, {{t|da|halløj}} {{qualifier|informal}}\n* Dhivehi: {{t|dv|އައްސަލާމު ޢަލައިކުމް}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|hallo}}, {{tt+|nl|hoi}}, {{tt+|nl|hai}}, {{tt+|nl|hé}}, {{tt+|nl|dag}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt+|nl|goeiedag}}, {{tt+|nl|goededag}}, {{tt+|nl|goedendag}}, {{tt+|nl|goeiendag}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|saluton}}\n* Estonian: {{tt+|et|tere}}, {{tt+|et|hei}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|hey}}, {{tt|fo|halló}}, {{tt|fo|góðan dag}}\n* Fijian: {{tt+|fj|bula}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|terve}}, {{tt+|fi|moi}}, {{tt+|fi|hei}}, {{tt+|fi|moikka}}\n* Fox: {{tt|sac|ahô}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|bonjour}}, {{tt+|fr|salut}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt+|fr|coucou}}{{qualifier|informal}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{tt|fy|hallo}}, {{tt|fy|hoi}}\n* Friulian: {{tt|fur|mandi}}\n* Fula: {{t|ff|mihofnima}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|ola}}, {{tt|gl|oula}}, {{tt|gl|ouga}}\n* Georgian: {{tt+|ka|გამარჯობა}}, {{t|ka|ჰეი}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|hallo}}, {{tt+|de|guten Tag}}, {{tt+|de|servus}}, {{tt+|de|moin}}, {{tt+|de|grüß Gott}} {{qualifier|Southern German, Austria}}, {{tt+|de|Tag}} (shortened form of guten Tag)\n*: Alemannic German: {{tt|gsw|grüezi}}, {{tt|gsw|sälü}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt|gsw|sali}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt|gsw|hoi}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt|gsw|hello