o|alt=hallo!}}, {{tt|de|halloho|alt=halloho!}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt|he|הלו|tr=hálo}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt|hu|[[jól]] [[vagy]]?}}, {{tt|hu|[[magad]][[-nál|nál]] [[vagy]]?}}, {{tt|hu|[[ész]][[-nél|nél]] [[vagy]]?}}, {{tt|hu|[[ész|esz]][[-ed|ed]][[-nél|nél]] [[vagy]]?}}, {{tt|hu|[[normális]] [[vagy]]?}} {{q|rude}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|halló|alt=halló!}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|ciao}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|やれやれ|tr=yareyare}} {{qualifier|formal and informal}}, {{tt|ja|やれやれだぜ|tr=yareyare daze}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt|ja|[[大丈夫]]？|tr=daijōbu?}} {{qualifier|formal and informal}}, {{tt|ja|大丈夫かよ|tr=daijōbu kayo?}} {{qualifier|more informal}}, {{tt|ja|[[マジ]]？|tr=maji?}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt|ja|[[マジかよ]]？|tr=maji kayo?}} {{qualifier|more informal}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|[[ало]]оо?}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|nb|hallo}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|hallo}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|acorda}}, {{tt+|pt|alô}}\n* Romanian: {{tt|ro|aloo}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|здра́сте}}, {{t|ru|здра́сте Но́вый Го́д}}\n* Slovene: {{tt|sl|haló!}}\n* Swedish: {{tt|sv|men hallå}}, {{tt|sv|hallå där}}\n* Tagalog: {{tt+|tl|hoy|alt=hoy!}}, {{tt|tl|huy|alt=huy!}}, {{tt|tl|oy|alt=oy!}}/{{tt+|tl|oi|alt=oi!}}, {{tt|tl|uy|alt=uy!}}/{{tt|tl|ui|alt=ui!}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt+|vi|này!}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|expression of puzzlement}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Afrikaans: {{t-needed|af}}\n* Arabic: {{t-needed|ar}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{tt|aii|ܐܲܠܘܼ}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt+|be|але́}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|моля}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|conill!}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t-needed|cmn}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|hallo|alt=hallo?}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|hallo|alt=hallo!}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|oho}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|ouah}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{tt|fy|hallo|alt=hallo!}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|hallo}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt|he|הלו|tr=hálo}}\n* Hindi: {{tt|hi|tr=kya}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|halló}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|本当？|tr=hontō}} {{q|Sure?|formal}}, {{tt|ja|冗談だろ？|tr=jōdan daro}} {{q|You are joking, formal and informal}}, {{tt+|ja|大丈夫？|tr=daijōbu?}} {{q|Are you all right?|formal and informal}}, {{tt|ja|大丈夫かよ？|tr=daijōbu kayo?}} {{q|Are you all right?|more informal}}, {{tt+|ja|マジ？|tr=maji?}} {{q|Are you sure?, You're kidding!|informal}}, {{tt|ja|マジかよ|tr=maji kayo?}} {{q|Are you sure?, You're kidding!|more informal}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|hei}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t-needed|nn}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt|pt|o que}}, {{tt+|pt|oi?}}\n* Romanian: {{tt|ro|ia uite}}\n* Slovene: {{tt|sl|hêj!}}\n* Swedish: {{tt|sv|men hallå}}\n* Tagalog: {{tt|tl|uy|alt=uy?!}}/{{tt|tl|ui|alt=ui?!}}, {{tt|tl|huy|alt=huy?!}}, {{tt|tl|oy|alt=oy?!}}/{{tt+|tl|oi|alt=oi?!}}, {{tt+|tl|hoy|alt=hoy?!}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt|vi|ôi trời!}}\n* Zazaki: {{tt|zza|merhebaa}}, {{tt+|zza|way}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Fijian: {{t+check|fj|bula}}\n* Irish: {{t-check|ga|haló}}\n* Nahuatl: {{t+check|nah|niltze}}\n* Nepali: {{t+check|ne|नमस्कार}}\n* Tatar: {{t-check|tt|[[isänme]](sez)!}}, {{t-check|tt|[[sälâm]]!}} (1), {{t-check|tt|allo}}, {{t-check|tt|hallow}} (2)\n* Urdu: {{t+check|ur|آداب|tr=ādāb}}, {{t-check|ur|السلام علیکم|tr=āssālam ‘alaykum}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|chào}} ({{t+|vi|ông}}, {{t+|vi|bà}}, {{t+|vi|cô}}, {{t+|vi|anh}}, {{t+|vi|chị}}, {{t+|vi|em}}, {{t|vi|quí vị}}) {{attention|vi|please add qualifier for each one on gender and relative social status of person addressed}}\n* Woiwurrung: {{t-check|wyi|gudjinna}}, {{t-check|wyi|wawa}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====See also====\n* [[:Category:English greetings]]\n* {{pedia}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|s|es}}\n\n# \"[[hello#Interjection|Hello]]!\" or an equivalent greeting.\n#: {{ux|en|They gave each other a quick '''hello''' when they met, and went back on their merry ways.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=April 29, 2007|author=Stephanie Rosenbloom|title=A Beautiful Day in the Neighborhood|work=New York Times|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/29/fashion/29condo.html\n|passage=In many new buildings, though, neighbors are venturing beyond tight-lipped '''hellos''' at the mailbox.}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|en|greeting}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|say hello to my little friend}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb|+,~es}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[greet]] with \"hello\".\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=Records and Briefs in Cases Decided by the Supreme Court of Minnesota|year=1891|page=227|passage=She is there guarding and looking after the candy and the children generally, and she '''helloes''' and renders an exclamation that Maidie is crossing the street.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=Ohio State Engineer|year=1927|page=18|passage=He '''helloes''' to my daughter:{{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Mark Dolan|title=Do You Mind if I Put My Hand on it?: Journeys into the Worlds of the Weird|publisher=[[w:HarperCollins|HarperCollins''Publishers'']]|year=2012|isbn=9780007481873|passage=‘Hello Minka! Great to meet you!’ Minka seems nonplussed at what I thought was an uncontroversial opening remark. There’s an awkward pause. She then '''helloes''' me back. But that’s all I get.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2013|author=Ivan Doig|title=English Creek|page=139|passage=I had to traipse around somewhat, '''helloing''' people and being '''helloed''', before I spotted my mother and my father, sharing shade and a spread blanket with Pete and Marie Reese and Toussaint Rennie near the back of the park.}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=ehllo|Holle}}\n\n{{cln|en|calculator words|greetings}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|fr|en|hello}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA|hèllo|[h]èllo}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-LoquaxFR-hello.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|fr|interjection}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|anglicism}} {{l|en|hello}}, [[hi]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n{{cln|fr|greetings}}\n\n==Fula==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{rfe|ff}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{ff-noun|ngo|hellooji|ɗi}}\n\n# a [[page]]\n# one side of a [[wall]], a wall\n# a [[slap]] in the face\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Bah 2014}}"}}